===Etymology 1===
Probably from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|dague|lang=fro}} (1229), related to  {{etyl|oc|-}}, {{etyl|it|-}},  {{etyl|es|-}} ''[[daga]]'', {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Degen|lang=de}}, {{etyl|gml|-}} {{term|dagge||knife's point|lang=gml}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|daggardr|lang=non}}, {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|dager|lang=cy}}, {{term|dagr|lang=cy}}, {{etyl|br|-}} {{term|dac|lang=br}}, {{etyl|sq|-}} {{term|thikë||a knife, dagger|lang=sq}},  {{term|thek||to stab, to pierce with a sharp object|lang=sq}}.

In English attested from the 1380s.
The ultimate origin of the word is unclear. Grimm <ref>[http://germazope.uni-trier.de:8080/Projekte/WBB2009/DWB/wbgui_py?lemid=GM03434 Grimm]</ref> <!-- dead link -->suspects Celtic origin.
Others have suggested derivation from an unattested Vulgar Latin {{term/t|la|*daca}} "Dacian [knife]", from the Latin adjective {{term/t|la|dācus}}<ref>http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dacia</ref>. Chastelain (''Dictionaire etymologique'', 1750) thought that French ''dague'' was a derivation from German ''dagge'', ''dagen'', although not attested until a much later date).

The knightly dagger evolves from the 12th century. Guillaume le Breton (died 1226) uses ''daca'' in his ''Philippide''. Other Middle Latin forms include ''daga, dagga, dagha, dagger, daggerius, daggerium, dagarium, dagarius, diga''<ref>http://ducange.enc.sorbonne.fr/DAGGER</ref>; the forms with ''-r-'' are late 14th century adoptions of the English word).
OED points out that there is also an English verb {{term|dag||to stab|lang=en}} from which this could be a derivation, but the verb is attested only from about 1400.

Relation to Old Armenian {{term|դակու|tr=daku||adze, axe|lang=xcl}} has also been suggested<ref>{{R:xcl:Martirosyan|page=232}}</ref>.

